To create a chessboard in LaTeX using the FEN (Forsyth–Edwards Notation) system, you can use the `tikz` package along with the `chessboard` library. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do this:

1. First, include the necessary packages:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{chessboard}
```
2. Load the `fancyvrb` package to properly display the FEN string:
```latex
\usepackage{fancyvrb}
```
3. Define a command to display the FEN string as a verbatim environment:
```latex
\DefineVerbatimEnvironment{fen}{Verbatim}{formatcom=\ttfamily}
```
4. Now, you can define a command to create the chessboard with the given FEN string:
```latex
\newcommand{\drawChessboard}[1]{%
    \begin{fen}
    #1
    \end{fen}%
    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85,transform shape]
        \chessboard[boardfen=#1,showmover=false,showcoords=false]
    \end{tikzpicture}
}
```
5. Finally, use the `\drawChessboard` command with your FEN notation:
```latex
\begin{document}
\drawChessboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\end{document}
```
Replace the FEN string inside the `\drawChessboard` command with your desired chessboard state. The example provided is the starting position of the game.

When you compile this LaTeX code, it will generate a chessboard with the specified FEN configuration.

